Accessing the Tassili n'Ajjer with vehicles can be very tough south of the plateau. It needs good cars, excellent drivers, thorough knowledge of the area and most importantly, a perfect organisation.

Planet Djanet and  Doudou, the local trip organizer can handle that ! Here at the Oued Issemen (issama) passage, a rare  path that can get you to one of the many floors of the Tassili n'Ajjer plateau, on vehicule !

The white crowned wheatear or "Moula Moula" in local tamahaq. The nomad's companion, a bird perfectly adapted to the desert life and is said to be a good omen by the Touaregs. The Moula Moula associated the presence of nomads/tourist groups to the presence of food (leftovers) and so became less fearful in these areas. It mainly eats insects and small lizards. 
If you visit the Tassili n'Ajjer you will no doubt observe it closely during lunch stops or even while walking during the day ð¦ð·

title:
Cistanche phelypaea or "Ahlewan" in Tamasheq. A parasitic plant that bears bright yellow flowers. It is edible and is said to have medicinal properties (good for abdominale pain or even diabetes according to touaregs). It grows by parasiting nearby plants and the best ones are said to be those that grow on Calligonum (Aressou). To consume, locals harvest young shoots and cook the  underground part under ash or hot sand. It is also attributed aphrodisiac properties.

Sources : local touaregs and the book "Fleurs du Sahara"
